result.execSummary:
The defendant James D Fish was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Substantial Battery-Intend Bodily Harm [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Repeater], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(2).
  • Resisting an Officer [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant James D Fish in court with attorney Brian David Van Ells. Joan M. Korb appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Court reviews Petition filed by Defense to withdraw. Defendant James D Fish appeared by video conference. Attorney Brian David Van Ells appeared in Court. Joan M. Korb appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Discussion regarding Defendant's previous representation regarding inpatient treatment. Defense advises that County will facilitate treatment arrangements if Defendant is released on bond, but will not put him to the front of the line. Defense advises of medical insurance that will pay for inpatient treatment, advises that doctors at Winnebago have changed his medication, request signature bond or small cash bond. State opposes modification request, advises of incident in jail, transportation to Winnebago, presents Court with Jail report (Exh. 1). Court questions insurance. Defense/State present arguments. Court will not modify bond, wants proof that insurance would cover voluntary inpatient stay.

Defendant James D Fish in court with attorney Brian David Van Ells. Defendant James D Fish in custody. Joan M. Korb appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Defense requests that cases be set for trial and pre-trial, requests that bond be revisited. Defense requests bail be addressed before trial be addressed. State has received no new complaints from jail. Deputy Schwartz agrees. Court questions Defendant, who advises that he has not even received a verbal warning. Defense presents argument for reduced bond, advises of inpatient mental health evaluation at Bellin that would occur if released, advises that victim has moved to Oshkosh. Court makes statement that if he heard directly from Human Services that he would go directly for inpatient treatment, he would consider change back to signature bond.
